\begin{strip}
\begin{abstract}
\textbf{Background:} Subthalamic (STN) and pallidal (GPi) deep brain stimulation (DBS) improve health related quality of life (\qol) in people with Parkinson's disease (PD). To increase this improvement is necessary to identify the factors that influence the \qol. We examined these factors in a DBS cohort and specifically analyzed the \qol outcome in a group of patients whose clinical and demographic characteristics are chosen to preferentially perform GPi--DBS, following the patient-specific consensus approach for the selection of target.\\
% \textbf{Objective:}\\
\textbf{Methods:} This retrospective, observational, single center study includes \Sexpr{n_stn} patients with PD who underwent STN--DBS and \Sexpr{n_gpi} who underwent GPi--DBS. Multivariable linear regression was used to identify which variables have an impact on changes in \qol were assessed using the Parkinson's Disease Questionnaire (PDQ--39) at baseline and at the one year follow--up. Using a propensity score matching we compare the change in \qol between STN- and GPi-group balanced out demographic and preoperative clinical characteristics.\\
\textbf{Results:} Improvement in motor outcome (\Sexpr{mu3_imp}), a reduction of pain (\Sexpr{pain_imp}) and improvement of apathy (\Sexpr{sas_imp}) contributed independently to improvements in \qol In the matched cohort PDQ--39 SI mean was \Sexpr{d} points better in the STN group than in the GPi group not statistically significant (\Sexpr{p}).\\
\textbf{Discussion:} In a cohort of older patients, with worse cognitive performance and worse postural stability the DBS in GPi target shows no benefit on \qol compared with STN target. That may call into question the patient-specific approach for the selection of the target. The improvement of motor outcome, pain and apathy are factors that influence the \qol. Focusing the assessments and treatments after DBS on these factors may increase the improvement of \qol in people with PD.

\end{abstract}
\end{strip}
% =======================================
\section*{Introduction} \label{sec:introduction}
% =======================================

Parkinson's disease (PD) is a neurodegenerative disorder characterized by motor and non-motor symptoms with a profound impact on health related quality of life (\qol) \cite{schrag2000contributes, martinez2011impact}.  Deep brain stimulation (DBS) of the subthalamic nucleus (STN) or the Globus pallidus internus (GPi) is a well--accepted therapy for advanced PD with motor complications and able to improve motor \cite{lachenmayer2021subthalamic} and nonmotor symptoms \cite{dafsari2020beneficial} as well as \qol \cite{dafsari2018short, schuepbach2019quality}.\\
While the STN may be the first choice as DBS target in many centers, there is an ongoing debate about the optimal DBS target for PD \cite{lachenmayer2021subthalamic}. The evidence so far from the randomized control studies (RCT) comparing targets suggest no superiority from GPi or STN regarding the most common primary outcome, motor outcome \cite{deep2001deep, anderson2005pallidal} nor \qol as a secondary outcome \cite{deep2001deep, follett2010pallidal, weaver2012randomized}. Mainly based on the understanding of the outcomes of the US Veterans Administration study, suggesting a worse long-term neurocognitive and neuropsychiatric performance and a greater number of falls in patients with STN--DBS \cite{anderson2005pallidal}, it has been proposed to choose the GPi target in elderly patients with poorer cognitive and mood indices and/or and prominent gait impairment, axial symptoms or falls \cite{deep2001deep, follett2010pallidal, rodriguez2005bilateral}.\\
However, studies confirming the superiority of GPi in this patient profile are lacking \cite{lachenmayer2021subthalamic}. Therefore, the current retrospective single-center study aimed to determine STN-- and GPi--DBS outcomes with a particular focus on quality of life in a PD cohort that received target selection according to the proposed patient--specific approach.

