In total, the cohort included 202 PD patients who received bilateral STN or GPi DBS. 21 withdrew consent, 35 were lost to follow-up and 5 lacked PDQ--39. Finally \Sexpr{n_pat} patients were included for the analysis of which \Sexpr{n_stn} received STN--DBS and \Sexpr{n_gpi} GPi--DBS. As shown in Table \ref{tab:tableone}, the two groups had different baseline characteristics being the patients in the group of GPi older, with longer disease duration, worse \qol, less improvement in MDS--UPDRS--III in L--Dopa Challenge, with more dyskinesia scores and worse postural stability. Regarding MMS there is a statistically significant but clinically not relevant difference of less than 1 point. There were no differences in terms of LEDD, MDS--UPDRS--III in Off--medication state, activities of daily living (Schwab \& England Scale), insomnia, pain and neuropsychiatric issues (Hamilton and Starkstein scales). \\
In a subanalysis to compare the \qol between GPi and STN group we used a matched cohort in order to minimize the selection bias. The matched cohort included \Sexpr{n_match} patients, \Sexpr{n_gpi} patients in the STN group and \Sexpr{n_gpi} in the GPi group which only differed by the target as shown in Table \ref{tab:tablmatched} in the Supplements.


\paragraph{Change of variables after one year follow-up}
One year after DBS the patients showed a remarkable improvement compared to the baseline by MDS--UPDRS--III Off--medication (\Sexpr{mu3_perc_imp}), VAS worst pain (\Sexpr{pain_perc_imp}) and Marconi score (\Sexpr{marconi_perc_imp}). As expected, LEDD reduction was greater in the STN group (\Sexpr{ledd_stn_imp}) than in the GPi group (\Sexpr{ledd_gpi_imp}). Apathy worsened in both groups (\Sexpr{starkstein_perc_imp}). All the outcome variables are shown in the supplement Figure S2.

